<DOC><DOCNO> AP890916-0033 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0524EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-NuclearDisarmament     09-16 0198</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Nuclear Disarmament,0205</SECOND><HEAD>International Nuclear Disarmament Symposium Starts in Tokyo</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An international symposium on peace and securitythrough nuclear disarmament in the Asia-Pacific region opened todaywith criticism that the region was lagging behind efforts in Europe,officials said.   Meeting spokesman Kenichi Nakamura said 31 scientists from 12countries, including the United States, Soviet Union and Britain,were meeting at the Pugwash Conference.   It was started 34 years ago in Pugwash, Canada, at the suggestionof Albert Einstein.   Discussions at the meetings, most of which are closed sessions,will focus on political and economic issues and how they effectprospects for nuclear disarmament in the Asia-Pacific region,Kenichi said.   Yoshikazu Sakamoto, a professor at Tokyo's Meiji GakuinUniversity, said during a keynote speech that the nucleardisarmament movement in Europe has worked much harder than that ofthe Asia-Pacific region.   The major focus in the region has been disarmament at sea, whichis more difficult to accomplish than on land, he said.   Sakamoto said disarmament would promote economic growth andcontribute to democratization of the Third World.   Following three days of closed meetings, participating scientistswill report on the outcome of the conference Tuesday.</TEXT></DOC>